Welcome to Python for Beginners. This is the very first lesson, and by the time we are done you will know what Python is, why it is worth your time, and how to write and run your first line of code. No experience required. If you have never programmed before, you are in exactly the right place.

So, what is Python? Python is a programming language — a way of giving instructions to a computer. What makes it special is that those instructions are written in something that looks a lot like plain English. Python was created in the late 1980s by a Dutch programmer named Guido van Rossum. Guido wanted a language that was clean, simple, and genuinely enjoyable to use. He wanted it to feel approachable, not intimidating. He named it after the British comedy group Monty Python's Flying Circus — so yes, the language is named after a comedy show, not the snake. Python 1.0 came out in 1991, and today it is consistently ranked as the most popular programming language in the world.

Why should you learn Python specifically? Because it works everywhere. Web developers use it to build server-side applications and APIs. Data scientists use it to explore and analyse data. Machine learning engineers use it to train AI models. System administrators use it to automate repetitive tasks. Researchers in biology, physics, and astronomy use it for scientific computing. If you can only learn one programming language, Python is the strongest argument for that language being Python. It has an enormous ecosystem of free, installable packages, which means you rarely have to build something from scratch — someone has almost certainly already solved your problem and published the solution.

Before we write any code, there is one piece of Python culture worth knowing about. Run the command import this inside Python, and you get a short document called the Zen of Python. It was written by a developer named Tim Peters and it describes the values that guide the language. A few lines stand out. Readability counts — because code is read far more often than it is written, and clear code is professional code. Simple is better than complex — if you can solve a problem in a straightforward five-line way or a clever one-liner, the five-line version is almost always the right choice. Errors should never pass silently — when something goes wrong, Python should tell you loudly, not hide the problem. These are not just ideals. They shape how experienced Python developers write code every day.

One thing you will occasionally encounter is references to Python 2. Here is the short version: Python 2 is dead. It was officially retired on the first of January 2020. It receives no updates, no security fixes, nothing. If you find a tutorial using print without parentheses — like print "hello" instead of print("hello") — that tutorial was written for Python 2 and you should find a newer one. Always use Python 3. That is the only version that matters.

Getting Python on your machine depends on your operating system. On a Mac, the cleanest approach is to use Homebrew, which is a free package manager for macOS. Once Homebrew is installed, you just run brew install python and you are done. On Windows, go to python.org, download the latest Python 3 installer, and run it — just make sure you tick the box that says "Add Python to PATH" before you click install, otherwise your terminal won't be able to find it. On Linux, if you're on Ubuntu or Debian, sudo apt install python3 python3-pip python3-venv gets you everything you need.

Once Python is installed, the next thing to understand is virtual environments. A virtual environment is an isolated copy of Python that belongs to one specific project. Think of it like giving each project its own separate room with its own set of tools. The tools in one room cannot interfere with the tools in another. This matters because different projects often need different versions of the same package, and without isolation they will eventually conflict. To create a virtual environment, you run python3 -m venv venv in your project folder. That creates a folder called venv. To activate it on Mac or Linux you run source venv/bin/activate, and on Windows it is venv\Scripts\activate. Once it is active, your terminal shows the name in brackets at the start of the prompt, and every package you install from that point on stays inside that environment.

Speaking of installing packages — that is done with pip. Pip is Python's package installer. You run pip install followed by the package name, and pip fetches it from the Python Package Index, which is a public repository of over five hundred thousand free packages. You can also run pip freeze to see everything installed in your current environment, and pip freeze with a redirect saves that list to a file called requirements.txt. That file is what you share with teammates or commit to version control, so anyone else can recreate your exact environment by running pip install -r requirements.txt.

There are three ways to actually run Python code. The first is the REPL, which stands for Read Eval Print Loop. It is an interactive prompt where you type one line of Python, hit enter, and immediately see the result. It is perfect for quick experiments. The second way is a dot-py script — you write your code in a file ending in .py and run it from the terminal. This is how real Python programs are shipped. The third way is a Jupyter notebook, which is exactly what you are reading right now. Notebooks mix runnable code cells with written explanation, which makes them ideal for learning and for data work where you want to see output alongside your thinking.

And now, the moment you have been waiting for. Your first program. In Python, printing something to the screen is one line: print, open parenthesis, your text in quotes, close parenthesis. That is it. print("Hello, World!") and the computer responds: Hello, World! From there you can print any text, any number, any result of a calculation. You can print a personalised greeting to each name in a list. You can combine text and numbers in a single line. It is a tiny start, but every Python program you will ever write traces back to this same idea — give the computer a clear instruction, and it will carry it out.

That is the introduction. You now know where Python came from, what it is used for, and how to get it running on your machine. In the next notebook, we start writing real code.
